a publisher, a distributor,
or a vendor rep.

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:50.930
And we'll start with pricing.

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:53.660
Pricing sounds easy enough, right?

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:56.420
I'm going to sell it at $59.99,
and I'm going to go to market.

00:14:56.420 --> 00:14:59.490
But if you price too high, what happens?

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:02.130
Product will sit on shelves,
and you're going to end up

00:15:02.130 --> 00:15:05.660
possibly with product coming back,
and then it doesn't work for you,

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:08.400
the developer, or for the retailer,
or the distributor,

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:10.200
or channel partner that you've used.

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:13.850
So at the opposite end of the spectrum,
if you price too low,

00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:17.200
think about the customer
connotation out there.

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:21.110
If you have a product that's
selling for $4.99 on a shelf,

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:23.790
as a customer,
you're going to think that it's cheap.

00:15:24.010 --> 00:15:25.960
And I'm talking cheap
not in terms of price,

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:26.880
but the value.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:30.030
So price, when we think about setting
a price on a product,

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:32.560
is really the customer's perceived value.

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:35.780
So it's pretty scientific,
and it's very critical

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:37.260
to going to market.

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:41.220
So pricing is one of the key elements
that you're going to want to consider

00:15:41.220 --> 00:15:43.830
and think about where you are
before you go into the market.

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:46.020
And I think that's going to be a key
element in your approach to pricing.

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:46.080
So I think that's going to be a key
element in your approach to pricing.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:46.570
or a vendor rep.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:48.570
The second one is packaging.

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:51.130
So many of us here,
we've written a product,

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:54.630
we've got code we might be
selling via download right now,

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:58.740
or taking advantage of some of the
opportunities that Paul covered,

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:01.390
but we don't have a physical package yet.

00:16:01.450 --> 00:16:05.510
Packaging is extremely important,
because when you're in a retail setting,

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:07.380
think about it as a customer.

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:09.250
You're looking at a
whole wall of software,

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:11.150
and what's going to grab your attention?

00:16:11.160 --> 00:16:13.770
You as the developer are
not there to explain,

00:16:13.820 --> 00:16:17.240
to explain to a customer why this
product should be purchased over

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:19.010
a similar product in the market.

00:16:19.150 --> 00:16:22.540
So you want to make sure that
you've got an attractive box,

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:26.050
and that you leverage the real
estate on the back of the package to

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:27.920
call out the features and benefits.

00:16:28.030 --> 00:16:29.940
And I'm going to get more
into packaging later.

00:16:29.940 --> 00:16:32.730
And then the third piece
is marketing strategy.

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:36.180
Paul covered it a little bit,
but it's very, very important.

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:41.240
The process of bringing a product to
market doesn't stop with pricing it,

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:43.800
putting it in a box,
and getting it on a shelf.

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:46.800
So what happens once that
product gets to a shelf?

00:16:46.950 --> 00:16:50.590
Resellers out there in the
market are going to expect there

00:16:50.590 --> 00:16:53.800
will be some kind of marketing
effort behind it on your part.

00:16:53.870 --> 00:16:59.800
And that could be as high end as a
huge Target circular on a weekend,

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:03.800
all the way down to simple things
that are very cost effective,

00:17:03.830 --> 00:17:06.800
like being loaded on a demo
machine in a retail location,

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.210
or getting a shelf talker placed
under it to call out some features,

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:11.260
things like that.

00:17:11.340 --> 00:17:13.780
And this is just three of the
things that are pretty high level,

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:17.780
that you need to think about before you
decide which partner is right for you,

00:17:17.820 --> 00:17:20.580
a distributor, a publisher,
or a vendor rep.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:24.780
So given that, let's go ahead and look at
three different scenarios,

00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:27.680
and which partner can help you.

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:29.780
So let's assume that you've
got all three of these.

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:32.740
You've got pricing,
you've got awesome packaging,

00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:35.440
you've got a marketing budget set aside,
and you already know the

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:37.770
activities that you're going
to be able to do in the market.

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:40.780
In this case,
you can go straight to a distributor,

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:44.380
and then the distributor will
help you to aggregate product

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:46.760
and send to each reseller.

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:50.760
The good thing about a distributor
here is that if you as a developer

00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:54.760
were able to get your product
into one of these retailers,

00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:57.760
for you to sign an individual
contract with each and every

00:17:57.760 --> 00:17:59.610
reseller would take a long time.

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:02.760
A distributor,
you can sign one contract with them,

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:04.760
work out the details,
and leverage their existing

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:07.760
relationships with the resellers.

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:12.630
They will manage the inventory for you,
help you with the collections, returns,

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:13.740
everything.

00:18:13.740 --> 00:18:17.100
So a distributor is a really
good person to go to if you've

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:20.720
already got your market plan set,
your pricing, and a package version.

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:25.740
Notice there's one step between you,
the developer, and the resellers.

00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:28.740
This is going to be your
lowest cost to market,

00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:31.740
because only one other person
is handling your product.

00:18:31.740 --> 00:18:35.490
But let's say we don't have
all three of these yet.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:37.030
Then what do we do?

00:18:37.030 --> 00:18:40.290
One other partner that we
could go to is a publisher,

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:42.510
and the publisher in turn can
leverage their relationship

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:43.690
with these distributors.

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:46.320
So say we don't have packaging yet.

00:18:46.470 --> 00:18:49.450
We've got a price point for our
product because we know about some

00:18:49.450 --> 00:18:51.760
similar products in the market,
and we know the features

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:54.380
and benefits of our product,
and we've lined them up,

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:57.620
and we think we can charge a $10 premium,
or we want to go out at the same

00:18:57.700 --> 00:19:01.190
price and try to take market share,
but we don't have packaging yet.

00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:05.860
You can work with a publisher who in
turn will help you get packaging either

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:10.190
in-house or with a third-party vendor
that they've got relationships with.

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:14.750
The publisher will then leverage their
relationships with buyers at each of

00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:19.150
these resellers to help you place your
product and then help you to ship product

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:23.860
in through distribution and ultimately
end up on shelves at major retailers.

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:26.620
But again,
we've added one more level here.

00:19:26.620 --> 00:19:31.240
So when you need to go to a publisher
to help get packaging or pricing,

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:36.320
or even advice on promotional strategies,
it's going to add another layer of cost.

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:38.070
So keep that in mind
as we go through this.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:40.360
And then in the third scenario...

00:19:41.960 --> 00:19:44.080
Let's say we're very new to market.

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:45.890
We don't have a lot of this down yet.

00:19:45.980 --> 00:19:48.160
We might need help with everything.

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:51.280
We don't know which price
point we want to go out at.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:54.890
A marketing strategy might be
something that's completely new to us.

00:19:55.020 --> 00:19:59.270
A vendor rep is really somebody
that's going to partner with you and

00:19:59.600 --> 00:20:01.580
help you take your product to market.

00:20:01.580 --> 00:20:06.040
So these vendor reps usually already
have relationships with publishers,

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:09.120
distributors,
and buyers at all of the major retailers.

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:12.750
They will be able to partner with you,
give you trends,

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:16.660
specifics on each retailer,
which ones you might want to target.

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:20.540
They'll already know the certain
programs that each reseller has available

00:20:20.540 --> 00:20:21.950
for you to promote your product.

00:20:22.030 --> 00:20:24.200
At one retailer,
you might be able to do an

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:25.820
end cap with your product.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:29.120
Another retailer may not let you do that,
where you think,

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:31.450
I'm going to do end caps everywhere,
and that's how I'm going to sell product.

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:34.180
They'll help you to understand
the different nuances that

00:20:34.190 --> 00:20:36.080
every retailer has out there.

00:20:36.080 --> 00:20:41.220
They'll help you connect with packaging,
and they will help you to develop a,

00:20:41.340 --> 00:20:42.430
a promotional strategy.

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:47.580
So in general, a vendor rep will add the
highest level of service,

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:50.720
work with the publisher,
potentially to get packaging,

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:53.620
and ultimately you'll still end
up going through a distributor

00:20:53.620 --> 00:20:54.860
to get into a reseller.

00:20:54.860 --> 00:20:58.000
So I leave a distributor
up here on every page,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:02.420
or every slide, because in general,
you're going to be using a distributor

00:21:02.420 --> 00:21:04.900
to get in to one of the major retailers.

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:08.820
On some occasions,
there is the distinct possibility

00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:13.220
that you could go direct,
realistically in 90% of the cases,

00:21:13.220 --> 00:21:15.160
you're going to end up
using an aggregator,

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:18.100
a distributor,
leverage their existing relationships,

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:19.570
and get product in that way.

00:21:19.580 --> 00:21:22.590
So here,
we've got the highest level of service.

00:21:22.600 --> 00:21:25.460
You've really got a business partner
and your vendor rep that's going to walk

00:21:25.540 --> 00:21:28.640
you through all the steps of the way,
lead you in the right direction.

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:30.730
They're going to possibly
use the publisher to help

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:33.130
you develop your packaging,
and then you're going to end up

00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:36.160
with product at a distributor
to ultimately get it on shelves.

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:39.780
So, what about Apple retail?

00:21:39.890 --> 00:21:43.120
I'm one of the software buyers
for Apple retail and manage

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:44.880
the software assortment.

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:53.890
So if I were to meet with any one
of you and look over the product,

00:21:53.890 --> 00:21:53.890
what are we specifically looking for
to add products into the assortments?

00:21:54.530 --> 00:21:58.200
and we kind of have a
distinct assortment,

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:00.720
or we think that we do,
because we see our stores

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:03.900
as a bit different than a
typical retailer out there.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:08.380
The high level of service,
the creative bars, the studio bars,

00:22:08.380 --> 00:22:11.280
the theater demos,
we think that there's a lot

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:14.580
of value add to not only just
putting the product on the shelf,

00:22:14.600 --> 00:22:17.730
and everything that goes on behind
that is making sure we have the right

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:19.120
assortment for our customer base.

00:22:19.160 --> 00:22:22.720
So I'm sure that a lot of people here
have been into an Apple retail store,

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:26.390
and if not,
I have a two minute video clip

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:28.640
that's kind of going to go through
what Apple retail is all about,

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:31.270
and for those of you that have been in,
I'm sure you'll probably

00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:32.690
recognize some of the stores.

00:22:32.710 --> 00:22:33.810
So let's go ahead and roll that.

