00:26:23.660 --> 00:26:25.900
So, there's still definitely a place
for the product in the store.

00:26:26.290 --> 00:26:29.160
But as we were to look at what's
on the floor in the assortment,

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:32.570
consumer-focused is
what we go after first,

00:26:32.660 --> 00:26:35.000
and an extension of the Mac platform.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:39.190
So, when we're evaluating a title,
we really need to make sure that this

00:26:39.190 --> 00:26:43.040
is the right solution for Apple and
that it's enhancing the user's

00:26:43.040 --> 00:26:45.210
experience of their Mac hardware.

00:26:47.330 --> 00:26:50.060
So next, packaging.

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:53.240
Again, consumer focus,
knowing who that target customer is.

00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:56.240
If you've got a consumer app,
you want to make sure that you're

00:26:56.250 --> 00:26:59.420
speaking to the customer in
terms that they'll understand,

00:26:59.420 --> 00:27:01.830
letting them know how this
product will benefit them.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:06.100
Obviously using the appropriate logos,
calling out customers are now

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:09.310
looking for that universal logo,
so it acts also as a

00:27:09.310 --> 00:27:11.090
marketing piece for you.

00:27:11.090 --> 00:27:15.240
And product differentiation
on the packaging.

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:17.520
And I think packaging is
very important because,

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:19.980
like I said,
when you're walking through a retailer

00:27:19.980 --> 00:27:23.730
and you're looking at a wall of software,
you've really got three to five

00:27:23.830 --> 00:27:27.010
seconds to catch that customer's
attention so that they pick up your box.

00:27:27.070 --> 00:27:29.240
So I want to dig a little
bit deeper into this and talk

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:30.720
about what I mean on packaging.

00:27:30.720 --> 00:27:34.740
So here, on the left-hand side,
we've got the front of the box,

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:39.770
probably a high-resolution graphic that
kind of talks to what your product is,

00:27:39.770 --> 00:27:43.500
obviously the product name,
the appropriate logos.

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:44.370
And on the front,
you really want to make sure that

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:45.220
you're talking to the right people.

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:47.860
And on the right-hand side,
you really want to keep it kind of

00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:50.250
clean and not put too much text,
like paragraph form you

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:52.880
probably want to avoid,
maybe a couple of bullet points

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:55.160
on what the product does,
who the customer might be

00:27:55.160 --> 00:27:57.720
and how they'll use it,
or even like a tagline.

00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:00.430
But again, the front of the box,
since you're not in the store

00:28:00.450 --> 00:28:02.900
making an assisted sale,
this is what's going to get the

00:28:02.900 --> 00:28:06.280
customer walking down the aisle to
grab that box and want to know more.

00:28:06.280 --> 00:28:09.830
The back of the box is really where you
want to leverage your real estate and

00:28:09.830 --> 00:28:13.300
talk more about what the product does,
how it's different than products

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:15.190
that are out there in the market.

00:28:15.200 --> 00:28:27.100
The back of the box is really where you
want to leverage your real estate and

00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:39.100
talk more about what the product does,
how it's different than products

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:45.180
that are out there in the market.

00:28:45.250 --> 00:28:45.940
So that's packaging.

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:48.600
And third, price.

00:28:48.620 --> 00:28:50.240
So again, target customer.

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:54.370
If you've got a consumer application,
maybe an education title

00:28:54.370 --> 00:28:57.810
for first to second graders,
probably not going to go

00:28:57.810 --> 00:29:00.110
out at $100 price point.

00:29:00.120 --> 00:29:03.400
If you have a high-end productivity
app that's for a business

00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:06.110
user or a pro photographer,
you want to look at who

00:29:06.270 --> 00:29:09.730
that target customer is,
where it fits in with other products that

00:29:09.860 --> 00:29:12.220
are out there and priced appropriately.

00:29:12.240 --> 00:29:15.100
So I think pricing often gets overlooked.

00:29:15.220 --> 00:29:18.440
It sounds simple to just say I'm
going to sell at $199 or $299.

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:21.260
But there's a lot of science behind it,
and you really got to think

00:29:21.400 --> 00:29:24.230
about how that's going to affect
the success of your product.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:25.760
Again, differentiation.

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:29.760
Knowing how your product is similar
or different to other products.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:32.650
If there's a similar product
in the market and you've added

00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:35.170
new and improved features,
are you going to price at

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:38.300
the same price point as that
product and try to take share?

00:29:38.300 --> 00:29:41.240
Or do you think that your
features warrant a $10,

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:44.350
$20,
$30 price premium and go out that way?

00:29:44.360 --> 00:29:45.130
So it just depends.

00:29:45.150 --> 00:29:47.120
It depends on how you think
your product is positioned.

00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:49.820
And the third thing here is margin.

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:53.630
So at the end of the day,
this needs to make sense for everybody,

00:29:53.630 --> 00:29:54.290
right?

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:58.060
For the retailer, for the distributor,
the vendor, the vendor rep,

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:00.370
the publisher, and you, the developer.

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:02.290
So think about when you're setting price.

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:05.660
Once you've added up all the costs
that it takes you to get to market,

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.800
and then what is the retailer
going to require to justify the

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:10.570
shelf space in their stores?

00:30:10.580 --> 00:30:12.980
At the end of the day,
how much is left over for you,

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:15.120
the publisher, or you, the developer?

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:20.470
So if you sold a $100 title and
the retailer is requiring 30 points

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:25.750
of margin or 30%, then $70 is left
to flow back through that chain.

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:29.210
And after your distributor touches it and
you pay for the packaging and everything

00:30:29.210 --> 00:30:32.310
else that's helped you get to market,
you need to make sure that

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:35.820
the cost benefit is there and
that this makes sense for you.

00:30:37.520 --> 00:30:44.740
So, summary for Apple retail,
what are we looking for?

00:30:45.800 --> 00:30:49.490
Product that's an extension
of the Mac platform,

00:30:49.490 --> 00:30:49.490
universal apps, attractive price points,
and awesome packaging.

00:30:49.850 --> 00:30:50.700
What does this all mean?

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:54.740
Once you've met with an Apple buyer,
you've got all this in line,

00:30:54.750 --> 00:30:56.220
and they say, yeah,
we want to bring it in.

00:30:56.220 --> 00:31:01.220
Does this mean that of the 155 stores
that we have open worldwide right now,

00:31:01.220 --> 00:31:02.640
does it go into every single store?

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:04.800
And the answer is maybe.

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:06.690
And the answer is it depends.

00:31:06.700 --> 00:31:08.010
And it depends on the application.

00:31:08.020 --> 00:31:09.540
It depends on the price point.

00:31:09.540 --> 00:31:12.670
It depends on what other titles
are out in the market right now.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:15.460
But one of the good things that
we have is we're pretty flexible.

00:31:15.810 --> 00:31:17.440
We've got several different footprints.

00:31:17.470 --> 00:31:19.940
We're in almost every major market.

00:31:19.940 --> 00:31:21.900
We're in every major market in the U.S.

00:31:21.980 --> 00:31:25.860
So we can kind of pick and choose where
it makes most sense for that product.

00:31:25.920 --> 00:31:28.790
Now, probably as the developer,
you're going to say, well,

00:31:28.800 --> 00:31:30.500
I want to be in every single store.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:32.440
That gets me the most exposure.

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:33.780
But think about it.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:35.660
At the end of the day,
if the product goes into a store

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:38.390
and just sits on the shelf,
after some amount of time,

00:31:38.390 --> 00:31:40.930
the math isn't going to work,
and that product's going to

00:31:40.930 --> 00:31:43.770
end up coming back to the
distributor and then back to you.

00:31:43.780 --> 00:31:46.270
So we really want to work
together on this and make sure

00:31:46.310 --> 00:31:47.940
we put it into the right stores.

00:31:47.940 --> 00:31:50.640
And that's what some of our
footprints allow us to do.

00:31:50.640 --> 00:31:52.770
Now, say we went into half of the stores.

00:31:52.820 --> 00:31:56.040
What happens in the other half of the
stores is if somebody walks in and says,

00:31:56.100 --> 00:31:57.900
I want to buy such and such title.

00:31:57.900 --> 00:31:58.650
I heard about it.

00:31:58.720 --> 00:31:59.420
It's awesome.

00:31:59.480 --> 00:32:00.160
I want to buy it.

00:32:00.260 --> 00:32:02.130
Well, down here I have online.

00:32:02.140 --> 00:32:05.970
Every terminal and every single
retail store serves as a kiosk.

00:32:06.100 --> 00:32:10.300
So if a customer walks in and says,
I want the upgrade to this,

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:13.760
and we don't carry it on the floor,
we can walk them over to kiosk.

00:32:13.760 --> 00:32:16.940
They can type in all their
customer information,

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:18.280
credit card info.

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:19.330
It'll ship to their house.

00:32:19.490 --> 00:32:21.690
If it's a title that's over $50,
it'll ship free.

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:24.960
So three days later, they end up,
they've got the package at their door.

00:32:25.130 --> 00:32:28.730
So even if you are only in a
subset of the retail stores,

00:32:28.730 --> 00:32:31.260
you're virtually in every store.

00:32:31.260 --> 00:32:34.140
And then it becomes a
question of promotional.

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:36.940
How do we let those store associates
know that that product is there?

00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:38.400
And that goes back to
your marketing plan.

00:32:38.420 --> 00:32:41.530
And that's it for retail.

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:43.560
I want to go ahead and
introduce Eric Lambert.

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:47.070
now and talk about a
real life success story.

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:55.580
